highlights.description: We have not reconciled whether we are liberal or conservative in the Madison regional area
We are prideful about having Epic but we don't want to have the conversation about how that has driven the market rate of rent up
This person says my car was stolen and I did not want to press charges, just wanted to have a conversation because this kid feels like nobody cares about him
This person says I was an only person of color in my elementary school and boy was it isolating
The municipalities in the Madison area need to be talking to one another
We have to avoid poverty porn
Using shame as a tool to perpetuate a bad system
Holding multiple ethno-racial identities was a process Tina had to go through, even in a "diverse" place like Madison.
There is a disconnect for people of color when it comes to a sense of feeling "at home" in communities that might seem majority white.
Will intentionally drive to Milwaukee because the city is much more representative of people of color.
Fiscal conservatism and its effects on racial divides and inequities, people rarely talk about this.
On a salient issue in Madison (car theft), parenting, and Black and Brown families.
The socialization process is different for students of color in majority white schools.
Students of color resort to affinity groups in their institutions because they provide spaces where they feel represented/in community.
Questions how to hold herself accountable in not deeming marginalized individuals as mouthpieces for an entire demographic.
On the importance of communication (and language).
What the speaker wants her representatives to know: creating "true" community engagement; changing the culture
